An edge is represented [ai, bi] denoting that there is an edge from vertex ai to bi . An edge is called a bridge if its removal makes 
some vertex unable to reach another vertex.
Return all bridges in the graph in any order.

Tarjan's Smart Idea

Question:

When DFS reaches a node,
how do we know whether this subtree has another path back to ancestors?

That's where, we have--> 

tin[] -- Time when node is first visited.
low[] -- Smallest discovery time reachable from that node.

Example-->
Graph:

0
|
1
|\
| \
2  3
 \/

DFS order:

tin[0]=1
tin[1]=2
tin[2]=3
tin[3]=4

At node 3: Can reach:

3 -> 1
which has

tin = 2
Therefore:

low[3]=2

Final:

Node    tin    low

0       1      1
1       2      2
2       3      2
3       4      2


***Bridge Condition***

Suppose DFS edge:

u ---- v

where v is child.

If
********  low[v] > tin[u]  ********
then u-v is bridge.

Because child subtree cannot reach

u
or
ancestor of u through any back edge.

Only connection is:
u-v

Remove it → disconnected.
Hence bridge.


CODE-->
class Solution {
public:
    int timer = 1;
    vector<int> tin, low, vis;
    vector<vector<int>> bridges;

    void dfs(int node, int parent, vector<int> adj[]) {

        vis[node] = 1; 

        tin[node] = low[node] = timer++;  //current low = tin bcz they have visted only themself 

        for (auto neighbour : adj[node]) {

            if (neighbour == parent)
                continue;

            if (!vis[neighbour]) {

                dfs(neighbour, node, adj);

                low[node] = min(low[node], low[neighbour]);   //get low from its nearby shortcut route 

                // Bridge condition
                if (low[neigh] > tin[node]) {
                    bridges.push_back({node, neigh});
                }
            }
            else {
                // Back edge
                low[node] = min(low[node], tin[neigh]);
            }
        }
    }

    vector<vector<int>> criticalConnections(int V,
                                           vector<vector<int>>& E) {

        vector<int> adj[V];

        for (auto &it : E) {
            int u = it[0];
            int v = it[1];

            adj[u].push_back(v);
            adj[v].push_back(u);
        }

        tin.resize(V);
        low.resize(V);
        vis.resize(V, 0);

        dfs(0, -1, adj);

        return bridges;
    }
};
